<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Name:</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the National Farmers Union</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU represents more than 55,000 farming members in England and Wales and we have some 41,000 countryside members with an interest in farming and the country. The NFU welcomes the opportunity to make a submission to the Environment Audit Committee on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prevention and management of Invasive Alien Species</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU believes that rapid response plans for early eradication or containment are far more cost effective than waiting until an Invasive Alien Species </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(IAS) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has become entrenched and difficult to control.  In addition, there will always be situations where prevention may fail due to accidental escapes or via a new and previously unknown pathway for the spread of an Invasive Alien Species.  We need to ensure the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">European C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommission proposals do not impede the UK’s ability to respond quickly to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or reduce the effectiveness of current national controls.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The EU proposals should focus on key species that are a serious threat to the whole of Europe and where collective action is required by all Member States to prevent that species being introduced or establishing. Collective action by Member States to tackle the pathways or potential routes of entry will be more effective, than individual countries taking their own action. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many invasive species are found established on or close to agricultural land e.g. along waterways. Agriculture suffers economic damage caused by the invasive species and often on the frontline in terms of picking up the costs and impacts of Invasive Alien Species when they establish on farmland and along waterways. It is therefore in the interest of farmers to welcome work in this area.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In England there are many invasive alien species that are widespread in the countryside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> e.g. grey squirrels and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">muntjac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Some species, that could be deemed invasive, are being used commercially, e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">miscanthus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to supply </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biofuels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n ornamental species</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e.g. rhododendron, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could become designated an IAS of European concern preventing further trade. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The annual retail trade in rhododendron is worth £1million per annum. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> These all raise concerns for the agricultural sector.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The European proposals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Not p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">revent ‘normal’ business activity e.g. growing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">miscanthus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biofuel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Allow trade to adjust if a species is designated as IAS of European concern, and provide appropriate compensation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Not allow the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">costs of enforcement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fall unfairly on agriculture because the species is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">already widespread in the environment, for example, if water primrose or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">muntjac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deer become defined as IAS of EU concern and controls are put in place.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Not p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">revent innovation across the industry,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for example, by preventing access to new varieties of crops. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Not b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e developed in isolation from other EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roposals which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">seek to control imports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> e.g. European proposals on plant health and reproductive material regulations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recognise that some invasive species are of regional, rather than EU wide, significance.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Not a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">llow Member States to designate their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">own species as IAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a means</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to create trade barriers. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">According to the European Commission there are currently over 12,000 species present in Europe which are alien to the natural environment. About 15% (1,800) of these are invasive and they are rapidly growing in number. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Invasive non-native species are thought to be one of the biggest threats to global biodiversity, second only to habitat loss. There are almost 2,000 established non-native species in Great Britain and invasive non-native species cost Great Britain around £1.7 billion annually</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An invasive species is a species which has been introduced to an area outside its natural range and can cause a multitude of ecological, economic and public health problems within the new habitat as its population grows. The extinctions of numerous species around the world can be attributed to the negative effects of invasive species. When a species is taken out of its natural range and placed into a new habitat it is removed from its natural predators and any pathogens which help to control its population. Without these, population growth may become out of control and the invader can rapidly colonise its new habitat outcompeting native species.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In England there are many invasive non-natives that are common across the landscape. Below a few of these have been summarised to provide some context. It also provides a useful reference point across which the European </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roposals for Invasive Alien Species Regulation will need to work: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Water Primrose from South America smothers water bodies reducing native species and potentially increasing the risk of flooding. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Species of deer, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Muntjac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, Fallow and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sika</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deer. All are widespread in England and cause damage to crops, forestry and biodiversity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The grey squirrel can be found almost everywhere in England and is well known for displacing native red squirrels. They cause damage to trees, including commercial fruit orchards.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">American mink are predators of animals such as ducks and poultry, game birds and fish.  They take eggs and chicks in gull and tern colonies. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rhododendron is widespread on acid soils.  Its dense thickets shade out indigenous plants, preventing regeneration of trees. It is poisonous to livestock.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rabbits are widespread across England.  Rabbits are recognised as a pest on farmland and estimated to cause economic losses in excess of £250m annually. Losses affect grassland, cereals, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">brassicas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, root and market garden crops and young trees. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Himalayan Balsam</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is well established and extremely invasive across England. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is rapid-spreading on soft banks of water</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bodies, dominant, forming extensive monoculture stands to the exclusion of most other plants.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many invasive species are found established on or close to agricultural land e.g. along waterways. Agriculture suffers economic damage caused by the invasive species and often on the frontline in terms of picking up the costs and impacts of Invasive Alien Species when they establish on farmland and along waterways. It is therefore in the interest of farmers to welcome work in this area.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">NFU Position</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NFU believes that rapid response plans for early eradication or containment are far more cost effective than waiting until an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has become entrenched and difficult to control.  In addition, there will always be situations where prevention may fail due to accidental escapes or via a new and previously unknown pathway for the spread of an Invasive Alien Species.  We need to ensure the commission proposals do not impede the UK’s ability to respond quickly to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or reduce the effectiveness of current national controls. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is A European Approach Needed? </span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many Member States already spend considerable resources in dealing with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, but their efforts are not effective if they are dealt with purely on a national basis. The Giant Hogweed eradication campaign in Belgium, for example, will be undermined if the species reinvades from France.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It makes sense that there is co-ordination across European boundaries, as already happens informally. European regulations could put Member State co-ordination on a more formal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">footing, providing the same tools to address IAS and ensuring all Member States are taking the same approach to tackling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The EU proposals should focus on key species that are a serious threat to the whole of Europe and where collective action is required by all Member States to prevent that species being introduced or establishing. Collective action by Member States to tackle the pathways or potential routes of entry will be more effective, than individual countries taki</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng their own action.  In addition, the regulation should clearly recognise that some invasive species are of bio-regional significance.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Definition of ‘invasive alien species’</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We recognise the major threat invasive non-native species pose to biodiversity and economic activity, but measures to counter this threat such as banning the sale of certain species must be based on sound science, and justified by robust expert evidence and peer-reviewed information. The definition of ‘invasive alien species’ in the draft Regulation (Article 3(2)) does not require the impacts considered to be based on science. We foresee that there may be possible conflicts here with for example, the horticultural industry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, the definition of ‘invasive alien species’ (Article 3(2)) must take in to account the negative impact on the economy.  It should not be a conditional requirement that, as written, there has to be a threat to ‘biodiversity and ecosystem services and that may also have a negative impact on [….] the economy’. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">List of IAS of EU Concern</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Not knowing the IAS species of EU Concern actually makes considering the impacts of the draft Regulation very difficult. The proposed limit of 50 species (article 4(4)) on the list of IAS of EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oncern is arbitrary and has proven to be contentious.  Given the vast number of potential species that could be listed as IAS of EU concern it is sensible to constrain the list to some degree, otherwise the regulations become burdensome on Member States and subsequently businesses. Given the requirements for risk assessments (Article 5(1)) and action plans (Article 11) for each species identified, it would be unreasonable to list all 1,800 species at a European level currently deemed invasive aliens.  Therefore, while 50 species is arbitrary, there does need to be some constraint on designation as IAS of EU Concern. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The EU proposals should focus on key species that are a serious threat to the whole of Europe and where collective action is required by all Member States to prevent that species being introduced or establishing. Article 4(2(c)) should be amended to also prevent the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of invasive species. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The invasive alien species identified as being of European concern must demonstrate a negative impact on biodiversity and ecosystem services or the economy.  Plus it should be demonstrated that inclusion of a species on this list will reduce risks of future negative impacts. This should be recognised through an amendment to Article 4(2).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There must be a process to review the list at regular intervals to ensure the list remains relevant in future years. A similar review process should be required for the risk assessments and management plans. A review is proposed in Article 4(1) of the draft regulation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the concerns for agriculture</span><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and horticulture</span><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Europe has published draft Regulations on Invasive Alien Species.  Once the regulation is agreed it will need implementing rules agreeing at a European level. The list of Invasive Alien Species of EU concern is unknown, so no management plans can be drafted.  Therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the actions required to address any one species are unknown. This means, at this stage, it is difficult to understand the impact of the regulations on businesses because much of the implementing detail is not available.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The main concerns for agriculture come from the impact of the Regulations, particularly on species that are present in the agricultural landscape. These could be species that are widespread in England, e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Muntjac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deer or grey squirrels, or species used to produce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biofuels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">miscanthus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   In this context the potential issues for farming caused by this regulation are:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#016938; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Preventing </span><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">normal</span><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> business activity:</span></li></ul><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If a species is listed as an IAS of EU Concern it will prevent (Article 7) trade, reproduction and transportation except for the purposes of research and conservation, under strict conditions. There are several crops commonly growing in England which are non-native. Triticale is a commercial crop, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">miscanthus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and hemp grown for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biofuel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> production and cup plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">silphiumm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ grown as a feedstock for anaerobic digestion.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Miscanthus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and hemp have been encouraged by Government to meet the Government’s renewable energy targets. By being included as a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> IAS of EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oncern it would not be possible to plant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, grow or market </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">future crops</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This would undermine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Government’s renewable energy commitment and Government’s financing of renewable power stations. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some non-native crops are grown to protect the environment, for example, mustard grown to provide a cover crop to prevent soil run off. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> non-native species occur naturally and, as part of their management, products are taken from those species for sale.  Bracken could be used for fuel or deer control leads to venison as a saleable ‘by product’. Product sales can help fund management of the species. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our preference would be for species cultivated or used com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mercial purposes, as described </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should not to be included on the list of species of EU concern (Article 4) or, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this is not possible, appropriate derogations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in place to enable continuation of legitimate business activity. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The risk assessment proposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rticle 5(1(h))) does require a description of possible uses and benefits deriving from those uses of species. However, it does not say what weighting this consideration will have in the overall assessment.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is provision in the proposals for management of invasive alien species that are widely spread (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rticle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 17 &amp; 18).  This does not provide for the management of a crop for commercial purposes.  It is written for management primarily for eradication of the species, then population control or containment.  Furthermore, these crops should not be subject to restoration of the damaged ecosystem (Article 18).  Articles 17 and 18 should be amended to allow appropriate commercial activity as described above. Furthermore, Article 27 needs amending to allow the growing and trade in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">types of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">crops described above. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#016938; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Allowing trade to adjust:</span></li></ul><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals will place restrictions on the commercial trade </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of EU concern. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, full regard must therefore be given to commercial production processes and sufficient lead-in time must be given to allow all existing stocks to be sold and wound-down before any ban came into place. Early consultation with those sectors involved will be critical.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If a species is designated as an IAS of EU concern it will prevent trade in that species, except for transportation to research or ex-situ conservation institutions which should be completed in two years (Article 27).  Businesses are currently carrying out legitimate trade with species that could be designated IAS of EU Concern.  Therefore, business must be given reasonable time to adjust and compensation offered. For example, there is an ornamental trade in many species </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rhododendron and some species could, potentially, be designated IAS of EU concern preventing future trade. This trade has an annual retail value of over £1 million. Those holding stocks must be able to dispose of them for a fair return or receive reasonable compensation for the loss of those sales. The regulation needs to be amended to take this in to account.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#016938; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Costs of enforcement:</span></li></ul><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The draft European Regulation does not address how a Member State would carry out enforcement of the Regulations. It does provide sanctioning powers (Article 25) allowing competent authorities to impose administrative measures on legal or natural person who does not comply with the regulation. It is for the Member State to implement and decide where the costs fall. It is not clear how these sanctions would apply where an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that is already widespread in the countryside.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is of particular concern to the farming industry as many non-native species in England are located on or close to agricultural land, as non-native species using agricultural land for habitat or as a source of food. If one of those non-native species is designated an IAS o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f EU c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oncern it is not clear where the costs of managing or eradicating the species would fall.  It would be extremely unfair for the costs to fall on the farming businesses where the species had found suitable habitat, when those species are already well established and the farm businesses were not responsible for the introduction of the IAS. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#016938; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Trade impacts from MS designating own IAS</span></li></ul><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The draft regulation allows Members States to designate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IAS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of concern to the Member State under emergency measures and allow them to put measures in place to manage the IAS (Article 9 and 10).  The draft Regulation is not clear which parts of the regulation apply to Member </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tate species of concern. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This needs to be addressed and the position clarified to allow recognition of IAS of regional significance.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The concern for agricultural and horticultural businesses is that this, potentially, could create artificial trade barriers between Member States. That would be unacceptable.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#016938; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Supporting innovation</span></li></ul><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Regulations could have unintended consequences on innovation.  The proposals should not prevent innovation in agricultural production. It should not result in new constraints in plant breeding or the development of plant protection products e.g. preventing the use of key micro-organisms. We welcome the exclusion of micro-organisms from the scope of the regulation (Article 2(2(f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> &amp; g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">))). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Restrictions on the introduction of species may prevent farmers and growers from being able to react to markets and to grow new varieties of crops as and when they become commercially available. For example, the total annual market value of Rhododendron </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ponticum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> selections and hybrids with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ponticum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the parentage is c. £420,000. These plants in turn have an annual retail value of over £1 million.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#016938; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#016938; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Alignment with Other EU Regulations</span></li></ul><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">separate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proposals for European plant health and reproductive material regulations which seek to place controls on imports, similar to the draft IAS regulations. The plant health proposals also seek to ‘zone’ issues allowing MS to designate a ‘zone’ to manage a plant health issue, without imposing requirements on all EU MS.  The IAS regulations seek to deliver similar arrangements.  Therefore, it is common sense for this suite of draft regulations to seek greater alignment and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">avoid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> contradict</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> each other, around border controls and ‘zoning’ of activity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">16 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0.5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAq4AAAACCAYAAACZvl66AAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAABBSURBVFhH7dZBDQAwCARB6gpL+BdAwUWbzCUYmOyDiNmpbMdAAxrQgAY0oAENaODVBvZnNQIECBAgQIAAAQJfCFzJnlppS4/FSwAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==" width="686" height="2" alt="" style="margin-left:0pt; margin-top:-1.8pt; position:absolute; z-index:-65536" /></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.arkive.org/uk-invasive-species/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.arkive.org/uk-invasive-species/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>